<br>
The only thing that we have ever proven in these debates (and I've seen a handful since I been here) is that, yup, either theory (or a hybrid of the two) are still ultimately based on faith - no one was there to witness "the beginning."<br>
<br>
I could argue my points, and you could argue yours. Regardless of who has more to back up theirs, or who can tear down the other's evidence, the fact of the matter remains that there is no empirical evidence exclusively supporting each other [that both side would be willing to accept as exclusive].<br>
<br>
Furthermore, both theories are rooted in religion or the lack thereof (and as was once said, zero is still a number). Religion is the "core" of faith for all intents and purposes, so dragging that in here just complicates things more.<br>
<br>
I believe the Bible, I believe in G-od, and I believe in Creation. I can't prove any of those outside of simply using the 5 senses to realize that they are all true. And what you believe in could probably use that same argument.<br>
<br>
That said, any Christian who takes the Bible as the infallible Word of G-od (read: we agree to a set standard for "debate rules") I would be glad to show you my views and prove each point.<br>
<br>
As it stands now, we have no "reference" point - all arguments are rather relative and arbitrary. We have no measuring stick to compare to, or absolute truths to match up against. Without these kinds of foundations, you can't prove/disprove anything, or debate logically.<br>
<br>
It is an interesting topic though, and if the debate erupts I'll probably follow along and most likely get dragged in anyway - at least my words have been prefaced lol.<br>
